        "excerpt": "Now in the seventh year Jehoiada sent and brought the captains of hundreds... then he made a covenant with them and put them under oath in the house of the Lord, and showed them the king's son.",
        "body": "Jehoiada's preparation for the coup is a masterclass in the relationship between theological principle and practical wisdom. His first act is not to reveal the hidden king — it is to make a covenant and administer an oath. He binds the military leadership to the LORD and to the enterprise before showing them what the enterprise is for. This sequencing is deliberate and important: the restoration of the Davidic line is grounded in covenantal obligation, not merely in the political interest of its participants. The officers swear to the LORD before they swear to Joash.\n\nThe tactical plan that follows (11:5-8) is sophisticated. Jehoiada exploits the Sabbath guard rotation to double his available force without an unusual mobilization that might alert Athaliah's loyalists. One third of the Sabbath rotation stays to guard the palace, maintaining normal appearance; the remaining two thirds concentrate on the temple and the king. The plan ensures that when Joash is presented, he is already surrounded by armed men at every point of the temple compound. The coup succeeds not because it is improvised but because it is meticulously planned around a routine that Athaliah would not scrutinize.\n\nThe weapons for the operation come from the house of the LORD — David's own spears and shields (11:10). The narrator's specificity here is not military inventory; it is theological commentary. The weapons that protected David are now protecting David's descendant. The house of the LORD has preserved both the king (hidden six years) and the king's armaments (preserved from David's era). The sanctuary is not a passive backdrop — it is the active preserving space of everything the Davidic covenant requires.\n\nBy verse 11, the king is surrounded by armed guards from the south side of the temple to the north, by the altar and by the house. The coronation space has been secured. The visual image is striking: a child who has been hidden now stands at the center of a ring of armed soldiers, each holding a weapon from King David's arsenal. The reversal from the vulnerability of verse 2 to the security of verse 11 is the narrator's visual argument that God's covenant faithfulness is real and active.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Karat berit* (cut a covenant, v.4) — the standard idiom for covenant-making, probably originating in the cutting of animals in covenant ratification ceremonies (Genesis 15:10; Jeremiah 34:18). *Shabbat* as the operational window — the Sabbath is both the covenantal day and the tactical opportunity; its double significance is almost certainly intentional."
