        "title": "The coronation's five acts — crown, testimony, anointing, acclamation, and the constitution of covenant kingship (11:12)",
        "range": "11:12",
        "excerpt": "Then he brought the king's son out and put the crown on him and gave him the testimony; and they made him king and anointed him, and they clapped their hands and said, 'Long live the king!'",
        "body": "Verse 12 compresses the entire theology of Davidic kingship into a single sentence with five distinct ceremonial acts. Each act does something the others do not, and their combination constitutes what Athaliah's seven-year reign conspicuously lacked. The crown (*nezer*) marks the transfer of sovereign authority. The anointing (*mashach*) marks divine designation — the same act by which Samuel anointed Saul (1 Samuel 10:1), then David (1 Samuel 16:13), and by which prophets anointed Jehu (2 Kings 9:6). The popular acclamation (*yechi ha-melekh*, 'long live the king') marks the consent of the governed. All three are present; all three were absent from Athaliah's seizure of power.\n\nBut it is the fourth element — the Testimony (*edut*) — that most distinctively marks the theological character of this coronation. The *edut* is not a crown jewel or a scepter; it is almost certainly the Torah scroll that Deuteronomy 17:18-20 required every king of Israel to write out for himself and read daily, so that 'he may learn to fear the LORD his God, to carefully observe all the words of this law and these statutes.' Jehoiada places the document of covenantal accountability in the king's hand at the same moment he places the crown on his head. This is constitutive, not ceremonial. Davidic kingship is mediatorial — the king rules *under* the Torah, not above it. The priest who crowns the king simultaneously presents the law that limits the king.\n\nThis moment has canonical resonance extending beyond the Books of Kings. Psalm 2, the royal coronation psalm, describes the LORD's anointed as the one against whom nations rage in vain because the LORD has decreed, 'You are My Son; today I have begotten you.' Psalm 72 describes the ideal Davidic king as the one who brings justice to the afflicted and righteous rule to the nation. Every specific Davidic coronation in the historical books is the partial fulfillment of a promise that awaits its perfect realization. Reformed and dispensational interpreters agree that these coronation texts point beyond any specific historical king to the Messiah — the anointed one par excellence — though they differ on the precise shape of the fulfillment. What is unambiguous in 2 Kings 11 is that the narrator presents Joash's coronation as the renewal of the Davidic covenant prototype, the institutional form through which God's promised king would eventually come.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Nezer* (crown) — used of the high priest's diadem in Exodus 29:6 and of the royal crown in 2 Samuel 1:10; its use here suggests the sacral character of the king's office. *Edut* — testimony, witness-document; its use in coronation contexts appears only here and in the parallel 2 Chronicles 23:11, suggesting a distinctively Judahite coronation practice grounded in the Mosaic covenant."
