        "number": 5,
        "title": "Athaliah's irony, Jehoiada's precision, and the covenant renewal that completes the restoration (11:13-21)",
        "range": "11:13-21",
        "excerpt": "Then Jehoiada made a covenant between the Lord and the king and the people, that they would be the Lord's people, also between the king and the people.",
        "body": "Athaliah's final appearance is the chapter's most ironic moment. She hears the noise of the acclamation, comes to the temple, sees the king standing by the pillar according to the custom, and cries: 'Treason! Treason!' (*qesher qesher*). The repeated word signals her absolute disorientation. She who committed treason against the Davidic covenant — murdering its heirs, seizing its throne, importing its replacement religion — names the restoration of that covenant as the crime. Calvin's comment in his *Commentary on the Books of Kings* remains the best gloss: the cry of 'treason' is the instinctive reaction of every usurper who suddenly discovers that the legitimate order has survived them.\n\nJehoiada's instructions about her execution deserve careful reading. He orders her brought out *between the ranks* — outside the temple compound — and specifies: 'Let her not be put to death in the house of the LORD' (11:15). This is priestly casuistry of the most precise kind. Athaliah deserves death; that is not in question. But the means of her death must not defile the space of worship. The temple's sanctity is not suspended for the purposes of political justice, however justified. She is executed at the horses' entrance to the palace (11:16) — the exact threshold between sacred and royal space, where her regime ended and where she was put to death.\n\nThe covenant renewal of verse 17 is the chapter's theological climax, not its political climax. The coronation and the execution are the political resolution; the covenant renewal is the theological resolution. Jehoiada structures it in two tiers: a covenant between the LORD and the king and the people (the Sinai covenant renewed — 'they would be the LORD's people'), and a covenant between the king and the people (the political constitution of the monarchy). The immediate consequence is the people's destruction of the Baal apparatus (11:18) — the idolatrous infrastructure of Athaliah's regime. The reform is total and without hesitation: the temple, the altars, the images, the priest are all dismantled or killed in the same movement.\n\nThe closing verse — 'Jehoash was seven years old when he became king' (11:21) — is the narrator's final theological point, placed last for maximum effect. The survival of the Davidic line through Athaliah's purge, through six years of hiding, through the coup and coronation and covenant renewal, issues in a seven-year-old boy on the throne. The dynasty's continuity is entirely God's doing. No human strategist could have planned the scenario that preserved it. The child's age is not an embarrassment to the narrative — it is the proof of the narrative's central claim: the LORD keeps His covenant word, even when every human indicator suggests the word has failed.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Berit* (covenant, v.17) — the same word used in v.4 for the private officer-covenant; now it describes the public, three-party covenant of restoration. *Shaqat* (quiet, v.20) — the shalom-word used in Judges for the land at rest after a judge has delivered it (Judges 3:11; 3:30; 5:31; 8:28). Its use here deliberately frames Jehoiada as functioning in the judge-tradition, delivering the covenant people from an oppressor."
